      "gains": "Zero risk of double-assignment. Simpler mental model — one source of truth. No need for conflict resolution or compensation logic.",
      "sacrifices": "5-15 second unavailability window during database failover. Orders placed during failover must be queued and retried.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "AP with conflict resolution: Use distributed locks (Redis Redlock) for availability, detect and resolve double-assignments after the fact. Rejected: Redlock has known safety issues (Kleppmann's analysis), conflict resolution adds enormous complexity for 2 engineers, and double-assignment has real-world cost (two couriers show up).",
        "Multi-primary PostgreSQL (BDR): Would give availability during node failures but introduces write conflicts. Rejected: Operational complexity far exceeds team capacity."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "PostgreSQL over a dedicated distributed lock service (Redis/etcd/Zookeeper)",
      "gains": "Single data store to operate. Transactional guarantees for free. SKIP LOCKED is purpose-built for this workload. Fewer moving parts for 2 engineers.",
      "sacrifices": "Theoretical throughput ceiling lower than a dedicated lock service. PostgreSQL is a broader tool than needed for just locking.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Redis with Redlock: Higher throughput but weaker consistency guarantees. Additional infrastructure. Rejected.",
        "etcd/Zookeeper: Strong consistency but poor fit for relational queries (finding nearest courier). Would need two data stores. Rejected."
      ]
    },
    {
      "decision": "In-process cache over Redis cache",
      "gains": "Zero network hop for cache reads. No additional infrastructure. No cache-aside invalidation bugs. Trivially simple.",
      "sacrifices": "Each service replica has its own slightly-different view of courier availability. ~1-2s staleness per replica.",
      "alternatives_considered": [
        "Redis cache: Shared view across replicas, but adds infra, network latency, and failure mode. For courier pre-filtering (not assignment decisions), staleness is acceptable. Rejected as over-engineering."
